  "howToUseData":{
    "sections":[
      {
        "heading":"Who Is This Study For?",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"Christians who want to think more carefully",
            "body" :"Jude was written to people who already believed — but who were under pressure from teaching that twisted the faith they had received. If you are a Christian who senses that something matters about getting doctrine right, but are not quite sure how to think it through, this study is for you."
          },

          {
            "title":"People exploring what Christianity actually claims",
            "body" :"If you are not yet a Christian but are genuinely curious — wondering not just what Christians believe, but why they think it matters so much — Jude is a striking place to start. It is a letter written with urgency, by someone who believed the truth about God was worth standing up for. That raises its own questions worth sitting with."
          },

          {
            "title":"Leaders and group facilitators",
            "body" :"Jude deals directly with the challenge of false teaching within a community of faith — which makes it particularly relevant for anyone in a leadership or pastoral role. If you are guiding others through questions of doctrine, discernment, or how to handle people who have drifted, these three chapters speak to that situation with unusual directness."
          }
        ]
      },

      {
        "heading":"Individual or Group Study?",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"On your own",
            "body" :"This study works well for personal reading. The book of Jude is short — just 25 verses — but dense. Working through it a section at a time, writing your answers before moving on, will help you slow down enough to hear what Jude is actually saying. The reflection questions at the end of each chapter are worth sitting with honestly."
          },

          {
            "title":"In a group",
            "body" :"Jude is an excellent study for a small group, partly because it raises questions that can generate real discussion — about how to respond to false teaching, what it looks like to contend for the faith without being harsh, and how God's character grounds our confidence. The most productive groups are usually those where each person has worked through the questions beforehand, so that discussion starts from real engagement rather than cold reading."
          }
        ]
      },

      {
        "heading":"Group Leaders & Mentors",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"Working with a leader or mentor",
            "body" :"<p>It can make a real difference to have someone walking through this study with you — a pastor, a more experienced Christian, or a trusted friend who can help you think through some of the harder material. Jude covers topics that can feel abstract or even unsettling: judgment, apostasy, the danger of error within the church. A good leader helps ground those themes in real life.</p><p>At the end of each chapter, the <b>Share</b> button lets you send your written answers directly to your leader — via WhatsApp, email, or any other app on your phone. This lets them see what you have engaged with before you meet, and makes the conversation much richer.</p>"
          }
        ]
      },

      {
        "heading":"A Note on the Questions",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"Three kinds of questions",
            "body" :"Each chapter begins with a short set of <b>observation questions</b> — straightforward questions about what the text actually says, designed to make sure you have read it carefully before moving on. These are followed by <b>Bible questions</b> tied to specific passages, asking you to think about what the text means. Finally, <b>reflection questions</b> at the end ask what the chapter means for you personally."
          },

          {
            "title":"The observation questions matter",
            "body" :"It can be tempting to skip past the opening questions because they seem too simple. Don't. Jude is a carefully written letter, and the details matter. Noticing exactly who Jude addresses, what specific words he uses, and what examples he chooses is the foundation for understanding everything else. Slow down and look."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },

